defaultCCS commercialisation programmedefaultThe latest CCS Commercialisation Programme is tasked with 
defaultlaunching a process to ensure the general deployment of CCS for coal and gas by the 2020s. 
defaultFrom an early commitment to four CCS projects, currently there may be support for only one or two. As a bare minimum, the government should rapidly conclude negotiat
defaultions at 
defaultDrax
default and Peterhead, with a view to plant
default being operational
default by 2018 at the latest. 
defaultMore than that, the government should retain its commitment to four demonstration projects and consider returning to other projects under development, offering them 
defaultclear and speedy alternatives either through the CCS competition or via 
defaultCfDs
default. Sustained deployment is critical at this stage.
defaultIs the UK Government’s approach, set out in its CCS Roadmap, likely to incentivise development of CCS in the UK?defaultThe government’s 
defaultapproach lacks the necessary pace and scale. As noted above, currently the main drivers of CCS are reliant on effective government policy. The two key strands of government support for CCS are the EMR reforms and the CCS commercialisation programme. These 
defaulttwo processes must work in parallel, not sequentially, to ensure the maximum momentum, technological advance and robustness of the programme against possible future project cancellations.  At present there is a strong perception that the government is resi
defaultsting further CCS deployment until the commercialisation projects are underway.
defaultCould the successful development of CCS improve international efforts to mitigate climate change? What role could UK CCS play in this? defaultYes. CCS is acknowledged to be a crucial transitional technology for climate change mitigation. The UK has a crucial seedbed role to play, although there is a now a clear danger that other countries will move ahead more rapidly, so that the UK loses techno
defaultlogical and market leadership. 
